The frequency of abortions in Bulgaria is quite high. According to the health insurance company, in 2016 the number was 123 500, which translates into 16.7 abortions per 1000 women of the working age. The mean age of the women undergoing abortions during the age 20-24 remains quite high – 230. There is only one legal ground for abortion in Bulgaria – threat to women’s health or life, which are usually extended to cases involving malformations of the fetus. Pro-choice activists point that the legal regulation of abortion in this poor country heavily relies on the unpredictable character of medical exams.

Despite the changes in the legal framework and the significant reduction in the number of abortions performed, in 2012 there were still 16.7 abortions per 1000 women of the reproductive age in Bulgaria. In many countries, this number has significantly reduced to below 15 (not counting cases where abortion is illegal in case of existence of critical health reasons). Researchers point that Bulgaria is one of 3 countries, and among them the only one with so-called “glass ceiling” of abortion which doesn’t allow substantial decrease in the number.
